WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:08.760
Sherlock Holmes, The Blue Diamond by Sir Arthur Conan Doyle

00:08.760 --> 00:15.880
Text Adaptation by Bill Bowler Read by Wayne Forrester

00:15.880 --> 00:24.280
Copyright Oxford University Press 2002

00:24.280 --> 00:33.120
Chapter 1 An Old Hat

00:33.120 --> 00:42.880
My name's Dr. Watson and I'm a good friend of the famous detective Sherlock Holmes.

00:42.880 --> 00:52.320
The two days after Christmas last year, I went to his house at 221B Baker Street.

00:52.320 --> 00:57.360
I wanted to say, Happy Christmas to him.

00:57.360 --> 01:02.520
When I arrived, I found him in the sitting room.

01:02.520 --> 01:08.000
He was by the window with some newspapers next to him.

01:08.000 --> 01:16.400
There was an old hat on a chair near him, and he had a magnifying glass in his hand.

01:16.400 --> 01:21.840
You're working on something, I said.

01:21.840 --> 01:24.040
Shall I go?

01:24.040 --> 01:27.600
No, said Holmes.

01:27.600 --> 01:34.400
Sit down and look at that interesting old hat over there.

01:34.400 --> 01:36.920
I sat down.

01:36.920 --> 01:45.320
It was cold out in the street, but it was nice and warm in Holmes' sitting room.

01:45.320 --> 01:49.720
Why are you interested in that old hat?

01:49.720 --> 01:52.960
Is it something to do with a crime?

01:52.960 --> 01:55.440
I asked.

01:55.440 --> 01:57.080
Holmes laughed.

01:57.080 --> 01:59.720
Not a crime, no!

01:59.720 --> 02:01.320
He said.

02:01.320 --> 02:04.320
I got it from Peterson.

02:04.320 --> 02:09.520
The doorman at the Baker Street Hotel.

02:09.520 --> 02:16.800
He found it in the street and brought it here on Christmas Day for me to look at.

02:16.800 --> 02:27.280
He also brought a dead bird with him, a good fat Christmas goose at the same time.

02:27.280 --> 02:30.920
I gave the goose back to him this morning.

02:30.920 --> 02:38.520
He's cooking it at his house now, and he's going to eat it for dinner tonight.

02:38.520 --> 02:46.520
Oh, first it was a hat, and now you're talking about a goose, I said.

02:46.520 --> 02:50.560
I don't understand.

02:50.560 --> 02:57.240
Then let's begin when it all began, said Holmes.

02:57.240 --> 03:05.760
At about four o'clock in the morning of Christmas Day, Peterson went home after work.

03:05.760 --> 03:13.360
When he got to Tottenham Court Road, he saw, in the street in front of him, a tall man

03:13.360 --> 03:16.800
with a goose over his shoulder.

03:16.800 --> 03:21.960
Peterson walked behind him for some time.

03:21.960 --> 03:26.720
There were some young men in the street in front of them.

03:26.720 --> 03:35.760
Suddenly, one of them hit the tall man's hat off his head, and it fell into the road.

03:35.760 --> 03:45.200
Then the tall man tried to hit the young man with his walking stick, but by accident he

03:45.200 --> 03:50.640
broke the window of a shop behind him.

03:50.640 --> 03:56.240
At that moment Peterson ran to the man to help him.

03:56.240 --> 04:00.840
But the tall man ran away.

04:00.840 --> 04:05.880
Perhaps he felt bad about breaking the shop window.

04:05.880 --> 04:15.560
Perhaps he thought that Peterson, in his dormers' coat and hat, was a policeman.

04:15.560 --> 04:22.800
When he ran, he left his Christmas bird in the street next to his hat.

04:22.800 --> 04:30.920
The young men ran away at the same time, so Peterson took the goose and the hat home

04:30.920 --> 04:37.600
with him, and the next day he brought them here.

04:37.600 --> 04:45.560
There was an interesting little ticket on the goose's left leg, said Holmes.

04:45.560 --> 04:51.720
It said, for Mr. and Mrs. Henry Baker,

04:51.720 --> 04:57.160
we can find the letters H.B. in the hat, too.

04:57.160 --> 05:06.880
Oh, so the owner of the hat and the goose is called Henry Baker, I said.

05:06.880 --> 05:16.920
Yes, answered Holmes, but my dear Watson, this doesn't help us very much.

05:16.920 --> 05:21.000
There are hundreds of Henry Bakers in London.

05:21.000 --> 05:24.640
I gave the goose back to Peterson this morning.

05:24.640 --> 05:30.680
He went on, and I said to him, have this for your dinner.

05:30.680 --> 05:36.280
I didn't want it to go bad, you know.

05:36.280 --> 05:43.400
Did Mr. Baker put an advertisement in the newspaper about his hat and goose?

05:43.400 --> 05:44.960
I asked.

05:44.960 --> 05:46.920
No.

05:46.920 --> 05:52.520
I said Holmes, then, how can we find him?

05:52.520 --> 05:59.360
Well, perhaps his hat can help us, said Holmes.

05:59.360 --> 06:02.600
Here's my magnifying glass, Watson.

06:02.600 --> 06:07.800
Now, you'll be a detective for a minute or two.

06:07.800 --> 06:13.360
What can you tell me about the owner of this hat?

06:13.360 --> 06:18.800
I took the magnifying glass and looked at the hat.

06:18.800 --> 06:24.760
It was black, but old, and very, very dirty.

06:24.760 --> 06:33.440
I saw the letters H.B. in it, but for me, it was no different from any other old black

06:33.440 --> 06:34.440
hat.

06:35.440 --> 06:43.440
I can see nothing, I said, and I gave the hat back to my friend.

06:43.440 --> 06:52.440
Excuse me, Watson, you do see, but you don't think about what you see.

06:52.440 --> 06:53.440
Hmm.

06:53.440 --> 07:00.720
All right, I said, what can you see in this hat?

07:00.720 --> 07:07.160
The owner of this hat is an intelligent man, said Holmes.

07:07.160 --> 07:12.120
He was once rich and is now poor.

07:12.120 --> 07:17.840
His wife loved him once, but she doesn't love him now.

07:17.840 --> 07:21.440
And he's 30 or 40 years old.

07:21.440 --> 07:29.640
Well, perhaps I'm slow Holmes, but I don't understand, I said.

07:29.640 --> 07:35.160
Why is he an intelligent man, do you think?

07:35.160 --> 07:38.320
Holmes put the hat on his head.

07:38.320 --> 07:42.840
It came down to his nose.

07:42.840 --> 07:45.960
This is a big hat.

07:45.960 --> 07:55.400
A man with a big hat has a big head, and a man with a big head has a big brain.

07:55.400 --> 08:05.800
A man with a big brain thinks a lot, but you say he was once rich and is now poor.

08:05.800 --> 08:07.760
Why?

08:07.760 --> 08:10.960
The hat is three years old.

08:10.960 --> 08:14.880
I remember these hats were in all the shops then.

08:14.880 --> 08:19.400
They were very expensive too.

08:19.400 --> 08:23.480
Three years ago, this man bought a good hat.

08:23.480 --> 08:30.800
So he was rich then, but he has no money to buy a new hat now, so these days, he is

08:30.800 --> 08:31.800
poor.

08:31.800 --> 08:39.640
All right, I said, but you say he is in his 30s or 40s.

08:39.640 --> 08:42.480
How does the hat tell you this?

08:42.480 --> 08:49.120
Well, when I looked carefully at the hat with my magnifying glass, I could see some

08:49.120 --> 08:52.600
grey hairs in it.

08:52.600 --> 08:57.760
People usually get grey hair in their 30s or 40s.

08:57.760 --> 08:59.440
I see.

08:59.440 --> 09:01.640
But what about his wife?

09:01.640 --> 09:05.240
You say she doesn't love him.

09:05.240 --> 09:08.400
Because the hat is very dirty.

09:08.400 --> 09:14.000
When a woman loves her husband, she cleans his hat for him.

09:14.000 --> 09:15.000
Hm?

09:15.000 --> 09:17.000
Perhaps he hasn't got a wife.

09:17.000 --> 09:19.520
Yes, he has.

09:19.520 --> 09:21.800
Remember the ticket on the goose's leg.

09:21.880 --> 09:25.400
Ah, yes, I said.

09:25.400 --> 09:29.320
You have an answer for everything.

09:29.320 --> 09:37.160
At that moment, the door opened and Peterson, the hotel doorman, ran into the room.

09:37.160 --> 09:39.320
He looked very excited.

09:39.320 --> 09:44.560
The goose missed a home's, the goose, he said.

09:45.560 --> 09:48.000
What's the matter with a goose?

09:48.000 --> 09:49.000
Asked homes.

09:49.000 --> 09:54.240
Did it come back from the dead and fly off through the kitchen window?

09:54.240 --> 09:57.440
No, Mr. Holmes.

09:57.440 --> 10:02.000
My wife found this in the bird.

10:02.000 --> 10:05.120
Peterson opened his hand.

10:05.120 --> 10:10.880
There was a beautiful blue diamond in it.

10:15.560 --> 10:19.560
Chapter 2, the blue diamond.

10:25.560 --> 10:31.560
When Sherlock Holmes saw the diamond in the doorman's hand, he sat up.

10:31.560 --> 10:36.560
Well, well, Peterson, he said.

10:36.560 --> 10:40.560
What a wonderful thing to find in a goose.

10:41.360 --> 10:45.560
Do you know what you have in your hand?

10:45.560 --> 10:49.080
I think it's a diamond, Mr. Holmes.

10:49.080 --> 10:51.680
Is it expensive?

10:51.680 --> 10:55.800
Yes, it is, said Holmes.

10:55.800 --> 11:00.800
This is the Countess of Morker's blue diamond.

11:00.800 --> 11:04.000
It disappeared a week ago.

11:04.000 --> 11:05.880
How do you know that?

11:05.880 --> 11:07.680
I said.

11:07.680 --> 11:12.600
Watson, you must read the newspapers more often.

11:12.600 --> 11:16.560
There's an advertisement in the Times today about it.

11:16.560 --> 11:19.040
Here, look.

11:19.040 --> 11:22.520
Holmes gave the advertisement to me.

11:22.520 --> 11:25.680
Then Holmes spoke to the doorman.

11:25.680 --> 11:29.320
It's a very expensive jewel, Peterson.

11:29.320 --> 11:34.000
The Countess paid about 20,000 pounds for it.

11:34.000 --> 11:40.960
Last week, someone took it from her rooms in the Cosmopolitan Hotel.

11:40.960 --> 11:45.320
Now the Countess wants to get her diamond back.

11:45.320 --> 11:51.560
She says that she's going to give 1,000 pounds to the finder.

11:51.560 --> 11:54.080
1,000 pounds?

11:54.080 --> 11:56.680
Cried Peterson excitedly.

11:56.680 --> 12:03.080
Then, without saying more, he sat down in the chair between us.

12:03.080 --> 12:08.840
First, he looked at Holmes, and then he looked at me.

12:08.840 --> 12:14.840
The diamond disappeared five days ago, I think, I said.

12:14.840 --> 12:18.680
Yes, answered Holmes.

12:18.680 --> 12:23.840
They say a young man, John Horner, took it.

12:23.840 --> 12:28.080
Here's a newspaper report about the case.

12:28.080 --> 12:34.640
Holmes gave an old newspaper to me, and I read the report.

12:34.640 --> 12:40.280
A diamond disappears from the Cosmopolitan Hotel.

12:40.280 --> 12:48.560
The Countess of Morker's blue diamond disappeared from her room at the Cosmopolitan Hotel on

12:48.560 --> 12:52.080
the 22nd of this month.

12:52.080 --> 13:00.280
The police think John Horner, 26 years old, took the diamond from a jewel box when he went

13:00.280 --> 13:03.280
to repair the window in the room.

13:03.280 --> 13:12.600
James Ryder, the assistant manager of the hotel, told the court, I took Horner to the

13:12.600 --> 13:17.840
Countess's room, but then I went away for some time.

13:17.840 --> 13:25.120
When I came back, Horner wasn't there, and I found the open box, without the jewel in

13:25.120 --> 13:29.080
it, on the table next to the bed.

13:29.080 --> 13:35.200
A Catherine Cusack, the Countess is made, spoke next.

13:35.200 --> 13:40.880
I heard Mr. Ryder call, and I ran to the Countess's room.

13:40.880 --> 13:47.040
There, I found Ryder with the jewel box in front of him.

13:47.040 --> 13:55.080
The police found Horner at his home later that day, but they couldn't find the diamond.

13:55.080 --> 14:00.160
Later Detective Bradstreet spoke to the court.

14:00.160 --> 14:06.000
When I said, you're a diamond thief, Horner hit me.

14:06.000 --> 14:12.160
Soon after that, Horner told the court angrily, you've got the wrong man.

14:12.240 --> 14:15.640
I didn't take the Countess's diamond.

14:15.640 --> 14:18.080
I'm not a thief.

14:18.080 --> 14:25.880
Bradstreet then told the court, Horner went to prison once before for being a thief.

14:25.880 --> 14:28.920
I say he took the diamond.

14:28.920 --> 14:34.480
The case goes to the High Court next week.

14:34.480 --> 14:40.760
Well, that's the newspaper report about the diamond, said Holmes.

14:40.840 --> 14:46.880
Now we need to understand how the jewel left the Countess of Morka's room in the Cosmopolitan

14:46.880 --> 14:52.640
Hotel and arrived in Tottenham Court Road in a goose.

14:52.640 --> 14:58.280
You see Watson, there is a crime in this case.

14:58.280 --> 15:00.280
Here's the diamond.

15:00.280 --> 15:03.400
The diamond came from the goose.

15:03.400 --> 15:10.360
And the goose came from Mr. Henry Baker, the man with the old hat.

15:10.360 --> 15:16.840
I know you felt a little bored when I told you all about Mr. Baker, but now we must find

15:16.840 --> 15:18.840
him.

15:18.840 --> 15:25.760
Where and how does he come into the case of the blue diamond?

15:25.760 --> 15:30.520
The answer to these two questions is most important.

15:30.520 --> 15:33.840
But how can we find him?

15:33.840 --> 15:35.840
I asked.

15:36.000 --> 15:41.840
Through a newspaper advertisement answered Holmes.

15:41.840 --> 15:46.400
He took a pen and began to write.

15:46.400 --> 15:54.160
Did you lose a goose and a black hat some days ago in Tottenham Court Road?

15:54.160 --> 15:57.720
Are you called Henry Baker?

15:57.720 --> 16:07.160
Please come to 221B Baker Street this evening at 630 to get your things.

16:07.160 --> 16:08.160
There.

16:08.160 --> 16:13.160
That says it all, I think, said Holmes.

16:13.160 --> 16:16.280
Yes, but is he going to read it?

16:16.280 --> 16:17.280
I asked.

16:17.280 --> 16:22.200
Yes, Watson, I think he is.

16:22.200 --> 16:25.040
He's a poor man, remember?

16:25.040 --> 16:29.760
At the time he was afraid because of his accident with the shop window.

16:29.760 --> 16:36.160
But now I believe he feels very sorry about running away and thinks, why did I leave that

16:36.160 --> 16:38.720
bird in the street?

16:38.720 --> 16:44.120
Perhaps he looked for a newspaper advertisement about it yesterday.

16:44.120 --> 16:48.760
I think he's going to look again today, too.

16:48.760 --> 16:54.720
What's more, we've got his name in the advertisement, so I believe his friends are going to see

16:54.720 --> 16:57.920
it and tell him about it.

16:57.920 --> 17:03.120
Yes, I see, I said.

17:03.120 --> 17:09.840
Holmes gave some money to the doorman and said, Peterson, please go down to the newspaper

17:09.840 --> 17:16.280
offices and put this advertisement in all the evening newspapers.

17:16.280 --> 17:18.200
Very good, sir.

17:18.200 --> 17:22.080
And shall I leave the diamond with you, sir?

17:22.160 --> 17:24.400
Yes, Peterson.

17:24.400 --> 17:32.840
And I say, Peterson, after you leave the newspaper offices, can you buy a goose and bring it

17:32.840 --> 17:34.560
back here?

17:34.560 --> 17:39.440
We need a new bird for Mr. Henry Baker when he comes.

17:39.440 --> 17:46.080
Your family is eating the old one for dinner today, so he can't have that.

17:46.080 --> 17:56.120
The doorman went out of the door and down the street.

17:56.120 --> 18:10.600
Chapter 3 Mr. Henry Baker Holmes took the blue diamond in his hand and looked at it.

18:10.600 --> 18:14.560
What a beautiful thing, he said.

18:14.560 --> 18:21.480
Look at the wonderful colors in it, dark blues and cold whites.

18:21.480 --> 18:27.160
All big jewels make people into thieves and killers in the end.

18:27.160 --> 18:33.600
This one comes from the south of China, near the Amoy River.

18:33.600 --> 18:38.360
It's only twenty years old, so it's a young thing.

18:38.360 --> 18:44.560
And already, many terrible crimes are happening because of it.

18:44.560 --> 18:51.840
I'm going to put it in my safe now, and then let's write a letter to the Countess of Morca

18:51.840 --> 18:57.160
and say we have her beautiful blue diamond here with us.

18:57.160 --> 19:03.000
But Holmes, I said, I don't understand.

19:03.000 --> 19:07.800
Is that young man-horner innocent, after all?

19:07.800 --> 19:11.240
I don't know.

19:11.240 --> 19:18.120
And what about Henry Baker, the tall man with the hat and the goose?

19:18.120 --> 19:21.680
Is he the jewel thief, perhaps?

19:21.680 --> 19:26.040
No, I don't think he is.

19:26.040 --> 19:29.840
I believe he's an innocent man.

19:29.840 --> 19:36.800
I don't think he knew there was an expensive diamond in his goose, a jewel worth more than

19:36.800 --> 19:40.160
twenty thousand pounds.

19:40.160 --> 19:42.760
But let's wait and see.

19:42.760 --> 19:49.440
Perhaps Mr. Baker's going to answer our advertisement this evening, and then we can learn something

19:49.440 --> 19:51.440
more about him.

19:51.440 --> 19:57.840
All right, I said, I can come back after work this evening.

19:57.840 --> 20:02.280
I'm very interested in the answer to this case.

20:02.280 --> 20:05.280
Good, replied Holmes.

20:05.280 --> 20:09.080
Here is at seven o'clock.

20:09.080 --> 20:14.040
I got to Baker Street at six thirty that evening.

20:14.040 --> 20:22.280
There was a tall man already at Sherlock Holmes' front door when I came down the street.

20:22.280 --> 20:29.720
He wore a long winter coat and had a Scottish hat on his head.

20:29.720 --> 20:34.480
When I arrived next to him, the door opened.

20:34.480 --> 20:40.960
Mrs. Hudson, Holmes' housekeeper, said, good evening to the two of us.

20:40.960 --> 20:47.160
And we went in and upstairs to Holmes' room.

20:47.160 --> 20:54.440
Mr. Henry Baker, I believe, said Holmes to the man when he came in.

20:54.440 --> 20:58.360
Please, sit down.

20:58.360 --> 21:00.960
Holmes looked at me and smiled.

21:00.960 --> 21:04.520
Ah, Watson, good.

21:04.520 --> 21:07.560
You are here when we need you.

21:07.560 --> 21:12.560
Then he looked back at his other visitor.

21:12.560 --> 21:16.240
Is that your hat, Mr. Baker?

21:16.240 --> 21:20.080
Mr. Baker looked at the hat on the chair.

21:20.080 --> 21:22.240
Yes, sir.

21:22.960 --> 21:25.200
Oh, that's my hat.

21:25.200 --> 21:28.520
There is no question about it.

21:28.520 --> 21:36.720
He was a big man with a big head, an intelligent face, and grey hair.

21:36.720 --> 21:40.280
I remembered Holmes' words about him.

21:40.280 --> 21:48.720
He wore a dirty old black coat with no shirt under it, but he spoke slowly,

21:48.720 --> 21:52.200
quietly and carefully.

21:52.200 --> 22:01.400
I looked at him and listened to him, and I thought, yes, this is an intelligent man.

22:01.400 --> 22:10.160
He was rich once, but now he has no money, and things aren't easy for him.

22:10.160 --> 22:16.000
We found your hat and your goose some days ago, said Holmes.

22:16.000 --> 22:20.480
But we couldn't find you very easily, Mr. Baker.

22:20.480 --> 22:23.600
He didn't know your address.

22:23.600 --> 22:28.840
Why didn't you put an advertisement in the newspaper with your address in it?

22:28.840 --> 22:36.600
We waited and waited for an advertisement from you, but saw nothing.

22:36.600 --> 22:39.120
Mr. Baker smiled.

22:39.120 --> 22:42.400
Ah, I'm sorry.

22:42.400 --> 22:48.680
Advertisements are expensive, and I haven't got a lot of money these days.

22:48.680 --> 22:58.840
I had once, but not now, he went on, and, well, I thought those young men in Tottenham

22:58.840 --> 23:06.280
Court Road had my hat and my goose, and I didn't want to put an expensive advertisement

23:06.280 --> 23:09.640
in the newspaper for nothing.

23:09.640 --> 23:13.160
I understand, said Holmes.

23:13.560 --> 23:20.720
Now, before we say more, I must tell you something about your goose, Mr. Baker.

23:20.720 --> 23:26.200
I'm sorry, but, well, we ate it yesterday.

23:26.200 --> 23:34.280
You know, you ate it, said our visitor, and he stood up excitedly.

23:34.280 --> 23:40.000
Yes, well, we didn't want it to go bad, you see?

23:40.080 --> 23:44.440
But we bought a nice new goose this morning for you.

23:44.440 --> 23:47.640
It's on the table there, by the door.

23:47.640 --> 23:50.200
Is that all right for you?

23:50.200 --> 23:56.400
Oh, yes, yes, said Mr. Baker happily.

23:56.400 --> 23:58.800
He sat down again.

23:58.800 --> 24:08.040
And, let's see, I think we have your old goose's feet, head, and everything from inside it

24:08.040 --> 24:09.840
in the kitchen.

24:09.840 --> 24:12.400
Do you want those?

24:12.400 --> 24:14.440
The man laughed.

24:14.440 --> 24:18.040
No, no, no, he said.

24:18.040 --> 24:22.560
But I'd like to take that nice new goose home with me.

24:22.560 --> 24:26.200
Thank you very much.

24:26.200 --> 24:30.560
Sherlock Holmes looked at me with a little smile.

24:30.560 --> 24:38.040
Very well, he said to Mr. Baker, there is your hat, and there is your bird.

24:38.040 --> 24:39.040
Let's take them.

24:39.040 --> 24:45.320
Oh, and before you go, can you tell me something?

24:45.320 --> 24:47.680
Where did you get your goose?

24:47.680 --> 24:54.320
I know a lot about geese, and that was a very good bird, I can tell you.

24:54.320 --> 25:03.520
Well, sir, said Baker, he stood up and took his hat and the goose in his hands.

25:03.520 --> 25:10.640
I got that bird at the alpha, a pub near the British Museum.

25:10.640 --> 25:17.240
This year, the owner of the pub, Mr. Windigate, began a goose club.

25:17.240 --> 25:24.480
Every week, we all put five or six pence into a money box, and at Christmas time, we all

25:24.480 --> 25:28.120
had the money for a goose.

25:28.120 --> 25:32.320
With that, he said goodbye and left.

25:33.320 --> 25:37.240
Well, said my detective friend.

25:37.240 --> 25:39.680
That answers one question.

25:39.680 --> 25:43.520
Mr. Baker is not our diamond thief.

25:43.520 --> 25:45.560
Are you hungry, Watson?

25:45.560 --> 25:48.720
Ooh, no, not very.

25:48.720 --> 25:50.440
Let's eat later then.

25:50.440 --> 25:53.280
We must go to the alpha at once.

25:53.280 --> 26:02.240
We need to speak to Mr. Windigate tonight.

26:02.240 --> 26:10.440
To fall, to Mr. Breckenridge's.

26:10.440 --> 26:17.840
Holmes and I put on our coats and hats and went out into the cold winter street.

26:17.840 --> 26:21.000
The sky was dark over our heads.

26:21.000 --> 26:27.760
We walked east, and in a quarter of an hour, we stood in front of the alpha.

26:27.760 --> 26:33.800
Holmes opened the door, and we went in.

26:33.800 --> 26:40.480
In the pub, the owner, Mr. Windigate, gave us some beer.

26:40.480 --> 26:42.520
Is this beer good?

26:42.520 --> 26:44.720
Holmes asked him.

26:44.720 --> 26:48.920
I asked because I know your geese are very good.

26:48.920 --> 26:53.680
Mr. Henry Baker told us all about your goose club.

26:54.680 --> 26:56.480
Oh, yes.

26:56.480 --> 26:59.800
But those geese weren't our geese.

26:59.800 --> 27:04.960
They came from a man with a little shop in Covent Garden.

27:04.960 --> 27:08.240
Breckenridge is his name.

27:08.240 --> 27:12.680
Thank you, my good man, said Holmes.

27:12.680 --> 27:16.400
We paid for our beer and drank it.

27:16.400 --> 27:22.920
Then we walked out of the warm pub and into the cold night again.

27:22.920 --> 27:29.720
Now for Covent Garden, who said Holmes, and we walked down the street past the British

27:29.720 --> 27:31.720
Museum.

27:31.720 --> 27:39.320
Remember, Watson, it all began with a goose, but it finishes with seven years in prison

27:39.320 --> 27:41.840
for young Mr. Horner.

27:41.840 --> 27:49.360
Perhaps we can learn more about this interesting case in Mr. Breckenridge's shop.

27:49.360 --> 27:54.960
We walked south, and soon came to Mr. Breckenridge's shop.

27:54.960 --> 27:59.280
A Breckenridge and a boy were at the door.

27:59.280 --> 28:02.640
It was nearly time to close for the night.

28:02.640 --> 28:04.240
Good evening.

28:04.240 --> 28:08.480
It's a cold night, said Holmes.

28:08.480 --> 28:11.920
How can I help you?

28:11.920 --> 28:16.800
Asked Breckenridge, Holmes looked at the empty shop window.

28:17.800 --> 28:22.320
No geese, I see, he said.

28:22.320 --> 28:26.200
There are some in that other shop, there behind you.

28:26.200 --> 28:32.680
Ah, but I came to you because I hear your geese are very good.

28:32.680 --> 28:37.600
Breckenridge's birds are the best, he said.

28:37.600 --> 28:39.880
He said that.

28:39.880 --> 28:42.080
The owner of the alpha.

28:42.080 --> 28:44.680
Ah, yes.

28:44.680 --> 28:50.160
He had twenty-four of my geese two days before Christmas.

28:50.160 --> 28:53.160
They were very good birds, too.

28:53.160 --> 28:54.880
Where did you get them?

28:54.880 --> 29:00.880
I'm not going to tell you, said Breckenridge angrily.

29:00.880 --> 29:07.320
Again and again, people come and talk to me about those geese, and I don't like it.

29:07.320 --> 29:14.200
I paid good money for them, I took them to the alpha, and then I forgot all about them.

29:14.200 --> 29:19.440
And then all the questions began, where are the geese?

29:19.440 --> 29:21.920
How much do you want for them?

29:21.920 --> 29:24.600
Who did you sell them to?

29:24.600 --> 29:26.240
Why are people interested in them?

29:26.240 --> 29:28.080
I don't know.

29:28.080 --> 29:31.600
I aren't the only geese in London, you know.

29:31.600 --> 29:34.760
I know, said Holmes.

29:34.760 --> 29:38.640
But who asked you all those questions before?

29:38.640 --> 29:40.000
Not me.

29:40.000 --> 29:43.440
I had nothing to do with that, you know.

29:43.440 --> 29:46.400
But now I need your help.

29:46.400 --> 29:52.280
We ate a goose at the alpha, and I say it was a country goose.

29:52.280 --> 29:58.640
But my good friend, Dr. Watson, here, says it was a London goose.

29:58.640 --> 30:00.520
Which of us is right?

30:00.520 --> 30:02.560
It's an important question.

30:02.560 --> 30:06.080
Five pounds goes to the winner.

30:06.080 --> 30:13.120
Well then, you lose, and your friend is the winner, said Breckenridge.

30:13.120 --> 30:16.320
That goose came from London.

30:16.320 --> 30:20.960
I can't believe that, said Holmes.

30:20.960 --> 30:23.960
A pound says I'm right.

30:23.960 --> 30:29.040
Very well, said Holmes, and he took out a pound.

30:29.040 --> 30:34.840
I'm ready to pay, but I know you're going to lose your money.

30:34.840 --> 30:36.680
Breckenridge laughed.

30:37.440 --> 30:39.440
Break me the books, Bill.

30:39.440 --> 30:44.920
He said, the boy brought two books to him.

30:44.920 --> 30:48.840
Breckenridge opened the little one.

30:48.840 --> 30:52.680
This is my address book, he said.

30:52.680 --> 30:58.160
When people sell their geese to me, their addresses go in here.

30:58.160 --> 31:03.360
Country people on the left and town people on the right.

31:03.360 --> 31:08.840
The numbers, after every name, are page numbers in my big book.

31:08.840 --> 31:14.120
Read out the third name on the right, said Breckenridge.

31:14.120 --> 31:25.080
Mrs. Oakshot, 117, Brixton Road, number 249, read Holmes.

31:25.080 --> 31:29.440
Then, Breckenridge opened the big book.

31:29.440 --> 31:35.200
And this is my in and out book, he said.

31:35.200 --> 31:39.360
Let's look at page 249.

31:39.360 --> 31:41.280
Here we are.

31:41.280 --> 31:48.720
Mrs. Oakshot, what can you see for December the 22nd?

31:48.720 --> 31:59.760
Twenty-four geese from Mrs. Oak, read Holmes, all twenty-four to Mr. Windigate at the alpha.

31:59.760 --> 32:00.760
There.

32:00.760 --> 32:06.040
What do you say now, said Breckenridge?

32:06.040 --> 32:16.240
Holmes put his pound into Breckenridge's hand angrily.

32:16.240 --> 32:25.880
Chapter five, a week, little man.

32:25.880 --> 32:31.960
In the street, Holmes stopped, but suddenly, he wasn't angry.

32:31.960 --> 32:34.120
He began to laugh.

32:34.120 --> 32:37.120
You see, Watson?

32:37.120 --> 32:44.440
He said, Breckenridge didn't want to tell me Mrs. Oakshot's name and address at first,

32:44.440 --> 32:52.200
but later, when he saw he could easily get a pound from me, he told me everything.

32:52.200 --> 32:56.920
And he said something very interesting when he got angry.

32:56.920 --> 32:58.960
Did you hear?

32:58.960 --> 33:03.080
Other people are asking questions about those geese.

33:03.080 --> 33:10.800
Suddenly, there was a lot of noise from Mr. Breckenridge's shop behind us.

33:10.800 --> 33:13.800
We looked back at it.

33:13.800 --> 33:19.640
Breckenridge stood tall and angry in front of his shop door.

33:19.640 --> 33:24.680
A week, little man, stood in front of him in the street.

33:24.680 --> 33:33.200
Look, you, Breckenridge shouted, I don't want to hear any more about those geese.

33:33.200 --> 33:38.720
Mrs. Oakshot can come and speak to me when she wants, but not you.

33:38.720 --> 33:41.600
You have nothing to do with it.

33:41.600 --> 33:44.000
Did I get the geese from you?

33:44.000 --> 33:49.240
No, but one was my goose, I tell you.

33:49.240 --> 33:51.440
Crayed the little man.

33:51.440 --> 33:54.760
Then ask Mrs. Oakshot for it.

33:54.760 --> 34:00.120
But she told me, ask Mr. Breckenridge for it.

34:00.120 --> 34:03.760
Well, that's nothing to do with me.

34:03.760 --> 34:06.760
I don't want to hear any more from you.

34:06.760 --> 34:08.440
Do you understand?

34:08.440 --> 34:11.440
Now go away.

34:11.440 --> 34:17.680
Breckenridge closed his shop door angrily, and the little man ran off down the dark

34:17.680 --> 34:19.680
street.

34:19.680 --> 34:27.720
Perhaps we don't need to visit Mrs. Oakshot in Brixton Road after all.

34:27.720 --> 34:33.960
Said Holmes to me quietly, let's talk to that man.

34:33.960 --> 34:37.480
Perhaps he can help us.

34:37.480 --> 34:43.480
Holmes walked quickly up behind the little man and put a hand on his shoulder.

34:43.480 --> 34:47.880
The man stopped and looked back over his shoulder at us.

34:47.880 --> 34:49.880
His face was white.

34:49.880 --> 34:52.960
Who are you?

34:52.960 --> 34:54.920
What do you want?

34:54.920 --> 34:56.920
He asked weekly.

34:56.920 --> 35:01.040
Excuse me, said Holmes.

35:01.040 --> 35:04.800
But I heard your questions to that shop owner.

35:04.800 --> 35:07.200
I think I can help you.

35:07.200 --> 35:10.280
Who are you?

35:10.280 --> 35:13.520
And how can you help me?

35:13.520 --> 35:21.160
My name is Sherlock Holmes, and it's my job to know things other people don't know.

35:21.160 --> 35:25.600
But you can't know anything about this.

35:25.600 --> 35:30.080
Excuse me, I know everything.

35:30.080 --> 35:33.600
You want to find 24 geese.

35:33.600 --> 35:39.400
Mrs. Oakshot of Brixton Road sold them to Mr. Breckenridge here.

35:39.400 --> 35:44.200
He sold them to Mr. Windigate, the owner of the Alpha.

35:44.200 --> 35:49.200
And Mr. Windigate sold them to the people in his goose club.

35:49.200 --> 35:53.200
Oh, sir, this is wonderful.

35:53.200 --> 35:56.840
Oh, I'm very happy to meet you.

35:56.840 --> 36:00.200
Said the little man excitedly.

36:00.200 --> 36:01.400
You are right.

36:01.400 --> 36:04.800
I am very interested in those geese.

36:04.800 --> 36:08.760
Oh, more than I can say.

36:08.760 --> 36:13.560
Why don't we go to a warm room in my house for a talk then?

36:13.560 --> 36:17.920
I don't like standing here in the cold street.

36:17.920 --> 36:23.000
Holmes put out his arm and a cab stopped for us.

36:23.000 --> 36:28.440
But before we go, can you please tell us your name?

36:28.440 --> 36:33.440
The little man looked at Holmes and then at me before he answered.

36:33.440 --> 36:38.360
Hey, John, Robinson.

36:38.360 --> 36:42.240
He said, no, no.

36:42.240 --> 36:44.560
Said Holmes quietly.

36:44.560 --> 36:49.280
We'd like to know your real name, please.

36:49.280 --> 36:53.800
The stranger's face changed from white to red.

36:53.800 --> 36:56.480
Oh, very well.

36:56.480 --> 36:59.920
My real name is James Ryder.

36:59.920 --> 37:04.280
He said, well, well, well.

37:04.280 --> 37:09.840
Said Holmes, assistant manager of the Cosmopolitan Hotel.

37:09.840 --> 37:14.440
Now, let's get into the cab and go home.

37:14.440 --> 37:18.400
Then I can tell you everything you want to know.

37:18.400 --> 37:23.880
So, we got into the cab and went home.

37:23.880 --> 37:28.520
The waiter looked excited but said nothing.

37:28.520 --> 37:36.040
Holmes didn't speak at all in the cab.

37:36.040 --> 37:37.960
Chapter 6.

37:37.960 --> 37:45.840
One or two questions.

37:45.840 --> 37:54.800
When we arrived at 221B Baker Street, we got out of the cab and went in.

37:54.800 --> 38:00.320
Back in his sitting room, Holmes spoke at last.

38:00.320 --> 38:03.200
Please sit down, Mr. Ryder.

38:03.200 --> 38:06.240
Now, where were we?

38:06.240 --> 38:08.640
Ah, yes.

38:08.640 --> 38:13.640
You want to know what happened to those 24 geese?

38:13.640 --> 38:19.040
Or perhaps, what happened to one of those geese?

38:19.040 --> 38:26.520
You are interested in only one bird, I think, a white goose with a black tail.

38:26.520 --> 38:32.200
Oh, sir, Ryder said excitedly.

38:32.200 --> 38:34.960
Where did that bird go to?

38:34.960 --> 38:37.520
It came here.

38:37.520 --> 38:40.600
And it was a most interesting bird.

38:40.600 --> 38:44.520
He found something in it after it died.

38:44.520 --> 38:48.360
The most wonderful thing.

38:48.360 --> 38:50.520
Here it is.

38:50.520 --> 38:54.640
Our visitor stood up weakly.

38:54.640 --> 38:59.360
Holmes opened his safe and took out the blue diamond.

38:59.360 --> 39:04.040
In his hand, it was cold and beautiful.

39:04.040 --> 39:09.280
Ryder looked at the jewel but said nothing.

39:09.360 --> 39:12.320
Holmes spoke for him.

39:12.320 --> 39:14.640
We know it was you, Ryder.

39:14.640 --> 39:18.800
He said, sit down and have a drink.

39:18.800 --> 39:21.400
You look very weak.

39:21.400 --> 39:24.160
I gave Ryder a drink.

39:24.160 --> 39:29.160
He sat down and drank it quickly and looked at Holmes.

39:29.160 --> 39:33.760
I saw he was afraid.

39:33.760 --> 39:37.680
You don't need to tell me much, said Holmes.

39:37.680 --> 39:45.480
I know nearly everything about the case, but I have one or two questions to ask.

39:45.480 --> 39:50.200
How did you hear of the Countess of Morker's blue diamond?

39:50.200 --> 40:00.400
Catherine Cusack, her maid told me, said Ryder, I see.

40:00.400 --> 40:02.400
Holmes went on.

40:02.400 --> 40:09.640
So you and Cusack wanted to get the diamond and sell it for lots of money.

40:09.640 --> 40:15.800
You asked John Horner to come and repair the window in the room because you knew of his

40:15.800 --> 40:18.400
time in prison.

40:18.400 --> 40:24.560
When he left, you took the diamond from the Countess's jewel box.

40:24.560 --> 40:27.200
Then you called the police.

40:27.200 --> 40:29.800
They came at once.

40:29.800 --> 40:35.240
Because of Horner's time in prison, they believed he was the thief.

40:35.240 --> 40:37.640
It was all very easy.

40:37.640 --> 40:46.640
Then, oh, please, please, cried Ryder, now on the floor at Holmes's feet.

40:46.640 --> 40:48.720
Think of my father.

40:48.720 --> 40:50.360
Think of my mother.

40:50.360 --> 40:52.920
I never did anything wrong before.

40:52.920 --> 40:57.240
I'm never going to do it again.

40:57.240 --> 40:59.000
Please don't tell the police.

40:59.000 --> 41:02.480
I don't want to go to prison.

41:02.480 --> 41:06.600
Sit down in your chair, said Holmes coldly.

41:06.600 --> 41:13.600
You're crying now, but did you feel sorry for young Horner?

41:13.600 --> 41:20.440
He knew nothing of this crime, but the police believed he was a diamond thief.

41:20.440 --> 41:28.200
And so he went to court and he is now going to prison, all because of you.

41:29.200 --> 41:33.000
I can leave the country, Mr. Holmes.

41:33.000 --> 41:38.760
Then, when I don't go to court, Horner can leave prison.

41:38.760 --> 41:43.440
We can see about that later, said Holmes.

41:43.440 --> 41:54.240
But now, please tell me, Mr. Ryder, how did the diamond get from the hotel into a goose?

41:54.240 --> 41:58.440
And how did the goose get into a shop?

41:58.440 --> 42:03.040
And please tell the truth.

42:03.040 --> 42:06.280
Ryder began.

42:06.280 --> 42:14.720
When the police arrested Horner, I left the hotel with the diamond in my pocket.

42:14.720 --> 42:20.760
I didn't want to stay at the cosmopolitan, not with the police everywhere, looking at

42:20.760 --> 42:21.760
everything.

42:22.360 --> 42:28.120
So, I went to my sister's house in South London.

42:28.120 --> 42:34.240
She lives in Brixton Road with her husband, Mr. Oakshot.

42:34.240 --> 42:41.640
I saw lots of police officers on my way there, and when I got to Brixton Road, I was very

42:41.640 --> 42:42.640
afraid.

42:42.640 --> 42:44.920
What's the matter?

42:44.920 --> 42:47.200
My sister asked.

42:47.200 --> 42:52.760
I told her about the diamond thief and about the police arresting Horner.

42:52.760 --> 43:00.800
Then, I went into the back garden to smoke and think, what could I do with the diamond

43:00.800 --> 43:01.800
now?

43:01.800 --> 43:07.640
In the garden, I remembered my friend Maudsley.

43:07.640 --> 43:14.880
He began well, but he went bad, and in the end, he went to prison for his crimes.

43:15.400 --> 43:20.320
Perhaps he knows about selling diamonds, I thought.

43:20.320 --> 43:28.160
So I decided to visit him at his home in Kilburn in North London.

43:28.160 --> 43:33.800
But how can I walk across London with the diamond, I thought?

43:33.800 --> 43:40.760
I can't have it in my pocket, not with all those police officers in the streets.

43:40.760 --> 43:47.960
Then I looked down at the geese in the garden, and I thought of something.

43:47.960 --> 43:54.280
I knew one of those geese was for me, for my Christmas dinner.

43:54.280 --> 44:01.600
So I decided to take my goose there and then, and not to wait for it.

44:01.600 --> 44:06.800
I quickly caught a big white goose with a black tail.

44:07.320 --> 44:14.920
Then, I took the diamond from my pocket and put it into the bird's mouth.

44:14.920 --> 44:19.200
I felt the jewel go down its neck.

44:19.200 --> 44:24.240
With the diamond now inside the goose, I felt happy.

44:24.240 --> 44:28.320
I could walk to Kilburn and back easily.

44:28.320 --> 44:32.520
Then, my sister came into the garden.

44:33.280 --> 44:37.160
What are you doing with that goose, she said?

44:37.160 --> 44:42.520
I put my bird down and it ran off with the other geese.

44:42.520 --> 44:47.120
That's the goose I want for Christmas, I said.

44:47.120 --> 44:53.640
Very well, catch it, kill it, and take it with you, she said.

44:53.640 --> 45:01.480
Well, Mr. Holmes, I caught that bird, killed it, and took it with me to Kilburn.

45:01.480 --> 45:08.520
There, I told my friend Maudsley all about the diamond, and he laughed and laughed.

45:08.520 --> 45:14.960
We got a knife and opened the goose, but we couldn't find the diamond.

45:14.960 --> 45:19.120
I knew then something was wrong.

45:19.120 --> 45:26.760
I left the goose with Maudsley, ran to my sister's house, and went into the back garden.

45:26.760 --> 45:30.080
There were no geese there.

45:30.080 --> 45:32.120
Where are they all, Maggie?

45:32.120 --> 45:39.080
I said, in Mr. Breckinridge's shop, in Covent Garden.

45:39.080 --> 45:42.040
Were there two birds with black tails?

45:42.040 --> 45:43.680
I asked.

45:43.680 --> 45:52.160
Yes, there were James, she said, and to my eyes, one was no different from the other.

45:52.160 --> 45:54.720
I understood it all then.

45:54.800 --> 46:01.120
The diamond was inside the other goose, with the black tail, and that goose was now in

46:01.120 --> 46:04.320
Mr. Breckinridge's shop.

46:04.320 --> 46:11.000
I ran to Covent Garden at once, and went to Breckinridge's, but the geese weren't in

46:11.000 --> 46:19.040
his shop, and when I asked about them, he told me, I sold them all at once.

46:19.040 --> 46:23.120
But you must tell me, where are they now?

46:23.120 --> 46:28.480
I asked again and again, but he never told me.

46:28.480 --> 46:33.280
You and Dr. Watson heard him earlier tonight, Mr. Holmes.

46:33.280 --> 46:37.720
He never answered my questions.

46:37.720 --> 46:41.760
Now my sister thinks I'm a terrible brother.

46:41.760 --> 46:43.560
I'm a thief.

46:43.560 --> 46:50.800
I'm going to lose my good name, and I never got any money from my crime at all.

46:50.960 --> 46:58.000
Oh, what's going to happen to me?

46:58.000 --> 47:02.800
He put his head in his hands and began to cry.

47:02.800 --> 47:06.240
Holmes didn't speak for a long time.

47:06.240 --> 47:12.520
Then, in the end, he stood up and opened the door.

47:12.520 --> 47:15.520
Get out, he said.

47:15.520 --> 47:18.440
Oh, thank you.

47:18.440 --> 47:19.840
Thank you, sir.

47:19.840 --> 47:23.800
He said, Ryder, be quiet and get out.

47:23.800 --> 47:31.760
Said Holmes again, and with that, Ryder ran out of the door, downstairs, out into the

47:31.760 --> 47:35.520
street and away.

47:35.520 --> 47:43.360
After all, Watson said Holmes, it's not my job to do the police's work for them.

47:43.360 --> 47:46.680
And young Horner's going to be all right.

47:46.680 --> 47:50.000
There isn't going to go to court now.

47:50.000 --> 47:57.080
Without him, the police have no witness to say Horner was the thief.

47:57.080 --> 48:01.200
Perhaps I'm doing something wrong, but I don't believe it.

48:01.200 --> 48:06.320
I think I'm helping Ryder to be a better man.

48:06.320 --> 48:11.800
Send him to prison now, and you make him into a thief for life.

48:11.800 --> 48:13.960
But now he's afraid.

48:13.960 --> 48:16.880
He's not going to go wrong again.

48:16.880 --> 48:22.160
We found the solution to the crime, and that makes me happy.

48:22.160 --> 48:24.560
And it's Christmas after all.

48:24.560 --> 48:30.240
And Christmas is a time to be nice to other people, I believe.

48:30.240 --> 48:35.840
And now, Watson, let's ask Mrs. Hudson to bring in our dinner.

